WEBVTT

00:02.895 --> 00:04.628
♪ ♪

00:07.566 --> 00:09.916
[Grampa]<i> They say</i>
<i> women are like soda water.</i>

00:09.993 --> 00:12.419
<i> They go better</i>
<i> with a gallon of scotch.</i>

00:12.571 --> 00:16.473
<i> And when the weather's hot,</i>
<i> we drink a lot.</i>

00:21.188 --> 00:22.429
<i> And sometimes it's so hot,</i>

00:22.598 --> 00:25.582
<i> people open their windows</i>
<i> to let the air in</i>

00:25.675 --> 00:29.194
<i> and their secrets out.</i>

00:29.346 --> 00:31.438
-[whirring stops]
-No.

00:31.607 --> 00:35.617
No, don't go.
Your tiny feet are so cool.

00:38.614 --> 00:40.597
Wait, I know a place to go,

00:40.599 --> 00:44.460
where the people always say
it's too cold.

00:46.530 --> 00:48.630
[frustrated grunting]

00:49.775 --> 00:51.533
Get your own cooling duct!

00:51.610 --> 00:53.110
Typical. My entire life,

00:53.128 --> 00:54.961
you've never done
one nice thing for me,

00:55.114 --> 00:56.613
and I'm always kind and loving.

00:56.615 --> 01:00.893
So redirect that A/C or we're
moving you to a worse home.

01:01.044 --> 01:02.377
There is no worse home.

01:02.471 --> 01:04.229
I mean the one
they put veterans in.

01:04.381 --> 01:07.357
You monster! Elder abuse!

01:08.235 --> 01:09.476
What took you so long?

01:09.628 --> 01:10.977
I'm not sure
what you're talking about,

01:11.130 --> 01:12.312
Abe "Grampa" Simpson,

01:12.481 --> 01:14.907
but we need your help
with an investigation.

01:15.134 --> 01:17.242
And I mean now.

01:26.829 --> 01:29.329
They're digging up
these poor people's graves?

01:29.481 --> 01:31.481
Now, don't worry.
They're putting up a monument

01:31.575 --> 01:34.818
to the suffering
of these unfortunate souls.

01:34.911 --> 01:37.096
[truck beeping]

01:38.006 --> 01:39.489
What are we doing here?

01:39.583 --> 01:42.175
We're here because
when they dug up one grave,

01:42.269 --> 01:45.329
they saw something
no one should see.

01:45.497 --> 01:48.982
Come on, kids, let me show you.
Get your phones.

01:54.598 --> 01:58.492
Somebody snuck a second body
in here.

02:01.013 --> 02:04.948
And on that extra body,
we found this.

02:05.775 --> 02:07.000
[Lisa]
"Simpson and O'Donnell,

02:07.110 --> 02:08.685
"private investigators.

02:08.778 --> 02:10.629
Ask for Abe"?

02:13.134 --> 02:15.300
Grampa, you were
a private detective?

02:15.527 --> 02:17.302
Takes you an hour
to find your socks.

02:17.529 --> 02:20.547
All right, Wiggum, you showed me
what you wanted to show me.

02:20.624 --> 02:23.124
Now, in this country,
a man can say what he wants

02:23.144 --> 02:24.143
and do what he wants.

02:24.370 --> 02:25.960
Except on college campuses,

02:25.980 --> 02:27.587
where you can say
some things but not others

02:27.723 --> 02:29.297
and it's unclear which.

02:29.375 --> 02:32.542
Hey, you can leave anytime,
after you explain

02:32.711 --> 02:36.137
how your business card
got on that body.

02:36.231 --> 02:38.306
Fine, I'll talk,
but only at the home,

02:38.325 --> 02:40.734
with a nurse call button nearby.

02:40.828 --> 02:42.477
Those things
aren't even hooked up.

02:42.496 --> 02:46.373
Pushing the button
is my exercise.

02:47.317 --> 02:48.584
See?

02:51.230 --> 02:54.131
Oh, I never saw
that part before.

02:54.991 --> 02:56.175
You think it's hot today?

02:56.326 --> 02:58.826
It's nothing compared
to the summer of '82.

02:58.846 --> 03:02.422
<i> It was like living</i>
<i>inside the sun with the heat on.</i>

03:02.499 --> 03:05.091
<i> Billy and me had been partners</i>
<i> for a couple of years.</i>

03:05.244 --> 03:06.576
<i> There was plenty of work.</i>

03:06.595 --> 03:09.579
<i> Divorce cases,</i>
<i> roller derby hit-and-runs.</i>

03:09.673 --> 03:12.840
<i> But this particular day</i>
<i> was mighty slow.</i>

03:13.602 --> 03:15.677
Ah, nice shot.
You should be in the NBA.

03:15.696 --> 03:18.346
You, too, pal.
You look great in short shorts.

03:18.365 --> 03:22.492
You mean the shorts that
everybody wears now in the '80s?

03:23.186 --> 03:25.687
<i> Then she came in.</i>

03:25.764 --> 03:27.431
I was looking for a detective,

03:27.449 --> 03:31.192
but it seems I found
a mutual admiration society.

03:31.212 --> 03:33.270
Are you here to join?

03:33.288 --> 03:35.380
First I'd have to admire you.

03:36.458 --> 03:37.532
I'm Agnes Skinner,

03:37.701 --> 03:40.535
and I want you
to follow my boyfriend.

03:40.629 --> 03:42.387
Oh? Who's your boyfriend?

03:42.614 --> 03:45.873
A rich bald vulture
by the name of Montgomery Burns.

03:45.893 --> 03:47.208
Well, I think
he's cheating on me

03:47.302 --> 03:49.135
with someone younger and sexier.

03:49.304 --> 03:51.396
-I don't buy your story.
-Which part?

03:51.473 --> 03:55.125
The part where there's someone
younger and sexier than you.

03:55.218 --> 03:57.903
Mm. It just got
really hot in here.

03:58.130 --> 03:59.796
Towel me off?

03:59.798 --> 04:01.889
Ah...

04:01.984 --> 04:03.483
Are you my new mommy?

04:03.560 --> 04:06.578
'Cause I'm owed
a lot of tucking in.

04:06.655 --> 04:09.322
[sighs]
Uh, Daddy's, uh, busy, son.

04:09.475 --> 04:12.567
Wh-Why don't you play
with these handcuffs?

04:12.586 --> 04:13.585
Oh, boy.

04:13.812 --> 04:15.254
Hmm. If you're babysitting,

04:15.481 --> 04:17.981
I guess I'll take
my business elsewhere.

04:17.983 --> 04:19.165
Oh, hold on, hold on, hold on.

04:19.242 --> 04:20.759
What if I go with Agnes,

04:20.928 --> 04:23.487
you know, and kind of
check things out?

04:23.655 --> 04:26.156
Okay, but remember,
you're representing the firm,

04:26.174 --> 04:27.915
so act professional.

04:27.935 --> 04:29.342
Ah, yes.

04:29.419 --> 04:31.561
[scatting]

04:34.608 --> 04:36.308
Oh, I don't get a new mommy?

04:36.460 --> 04:39.185
I'll be your daddy
and your mommy, son.

04:39.280 --> 04:41.763
Now be quiet and leave me alone.

04:41.840 --> 04:43.023
And that was that.

04:43.117 --> 04:45.191
Now if you're finished,
it's Tapioca Tuesday

04:45.286 --> 04:47.602
and I'm jonesing
for something bland and lumpy.

04:47.696 --> 04:51.773
[all moaning]
Tapioca. Tapioca.

04:51.850 --> 04:53.350
Hmm.

04:53.443 --> 04:55.535
Slow down, there,
Humphrey Go-kart.

04:55.704 --> 04:57.612
What did your partner say
when he got back?

04:57.781 --> 05:01.949
Nothing, which isn't surprising,
because he never came back.

05:02.044 --> 05:04.118
Never came back?
What did you do?

05:04.138 --> 05:05.529
Got new business cards.

05:05.697 --> 05:09.699
"Abe Simpson and nobody,
private investigators."

05:09.793 --> 05:11.201
[low]
I'm not surprised.

05:11.203 --> 05:13.370
My dad never does
anything for anybody.

05:13.463 --> 05:17.149
Homer, let the policemen
give your dad the third degree.

05:17.225 --> 05:18.542
Wiggum, I'm done singing.

05:18.635 --> 05:21.486
But here's an encore for you:
get lost!

05:21.563 --> 05:23.547
Oh, yeah?
How'd you like it if we put you

05:23.549 --> 05:25.657
in an interrogation room
with a bare light bulb,

05:25.826 --> 05:30.053
no bathroom and a cold
steel chair with an uneven leg?

05:30.072 --> 05:31.854
I'd call that an upgrade.

05:31.907 --> 05:33.999
[electricity buzzes]

05:34.150 --> 05:35.742
Okay, fine, we'll leave.
For now.

05:35.894 --> 05:39.821
But I am officially declaring
you a person of interest.

05:39.989 --> 05:42.415
Wow, Grampa,
you're finally interesting.

05:42.492 --> 05:43.416
Can we hang out?

05:43.585 --> 05:45.635
-Yeah, but I ain't talking.
-Perfect.

05:50.742 --> 05:52.184
I can't believe it.

05:52.335 --> 05:53.593
Would Grampa really not
look for his partner?

05:53.745 --> 05:54.911
That's exactly what he would do.

05:55.080 --> 05:56.763
He didn't look
for his missing wife.

05:56.915 --> 05:58.431
He couldn't find a runaway dog.

05:58.584 --> 06:00.508
He didn't realize
I was lost at the zoo

06:00.527 --> 06:03.587
until the chimpanzee
in the car seat threw up.

06:03.589 --> 06:06.606
He still sends that monkey
birthday cards.

06:06.700 --> 06:08.441
Maybe I could get some answers

06:08.594 --> 06:11.094
from a forensic analysis
of the old business card.

06:11.096 --> 06:14.539
Lisa, I don't like it
when you dust for residues.

06:14.708 --> 06:15.874
Please, please, please.

06:16.025 --> 06:18.268
I promise I'll only look
for splatter.

06:18.286 --> 06:20.954
Okay, but put down newspaper.

06:21.106 --> 06:22.964
What the hell's a newspaper?

06:25.794 --> 06:27.627
Bart, there's blood
on this card.

06:27.779 --> 06:32.449
Type AB-negative, which is only
one percent of the population.

06:32.542 --> 06:34.559
Amazing. You can make
even blood boring.

06:34.711 --> 06:37.137
If Billy O'Donnell
had the same blood type,

06:37.305 --> 06:39.213
it could be him in the coffin.

06:39.307 --> 06:41.307
Coffin, eh?
You saying he's a vampire?

06:41.460 --> 06:43.217
[imitating Dracula]
Yes, he's a vampire.

06:43.311 --> 06:46.312
We must investigate
his blood. Bleh.

06:46.407 --> 06:49.315
You're treating me like a child,
and I love it.

06:49.410 --> 06:51.301
Say "bleh" two more times,
and I'm in.

06:51.394 --> 06:52.393
Bleh. Bleh.

06:52.562 --> 06:54.137
-Okay, blood type.
-[fingers snap]

06:54.230 --> 06:56.063
I know two people with
all the information in town,

06:56.158 --> 06:58.158
-but it'll cost you.
-[normal voice] How much?

06:58.310 --> 07:02.254
I'm afraid we're gonna have to
spend some time with them.

07:02.423 --> 07:05.924
Here's the medical techs
at my barium swallow.

07:06.151 --> 07:10.095
Here's me waking up because the
anesthesia wasn't strong enough.

07:10.172 --> 07:12.656
And here's the kink
in my esophagus.

07:12.749 --> 07:16.009
And here's us transferring
our slides to video.

07:16.178 --> 07:18.419
Transferring. Transferring.

07:18.439 --> 07:21.606
Now here's us transferring
our video to digital.

07:21.833 --> 07:25.110
Transferring. Transferring.
Transferring.

07:25.337 --> 07:27.237
[man]
Hey, can we get some service?

07:28.282 --> 07:30.765
Snoop to
your heart's content, kids.

07:30.784 --> 07:32.509
But remember, that information

07:32.527 --> 07:35.195
belongs to the people
of Springfield.

07:35.347 --> 07:37.956
Show them the respect
they deserve.

07:39.108 --> 07:42.368
O'Bannon. O'Brady.
O'Connell. O'Connor.

07:42.521 --> 07:44.187
Lot of Irish in this town.

07:44.206 --> 07:47.207
O'Day. O'Dell. O'de-o'doh.

07:47.301 --> 07:49.693
[gasps]
O'Donnell! Billy O'Donnell!

07:49.786 --> 07:51.361
Blood type: AB-negative.

07:51.363 --> 07:53.546
It's a match.
I'm taking this to Grampa.

07:53.699 --> 07:56.308
[gasps] Did you know
Lenny has only one butt cheek?

07:56.535 --> 07:58.727
No wonder he keeps
falling off his stool.

07:59.980 --> 08:01.480
Not my fault.

08:03.466 --> 08:05.484
Chief, it's the old man's
granddaughter.

08:05.635 --> 08:07.986
And you didn't want
to set up a stakeout.

08:08.063 --> 08:11.064
No, I wanted to. You didn't.

08:11.158 --> 08:12.824
Well, somebody did. Shut up.

08:12.901 --> 08:14.308
It's the same blood type.

08:14.402 --> 08:17.144
I bet you want to get right back
on that trail.

08:17.164 --> 08:19.889
That trail is 40 years old.

08:19.983 --> 08:23.243
Colder than the hands of
the orderly who puts my gown on.

08:23.411 --> 08:25.337
Hey, orderlies have
feelings, too.

08:25.564 --> 08:26.788
[crying]

08:26.898 --> 08:29.174
The DMV found
Billy's abandoned car

08:29.401 --> 08:32.585
on old Apple Blossom Parkway,
which is now

08:32.679 --> 08:36.181
the location of
the Springfield Nuclear Plant.

08:36.332 --> 08:37.407
Well?

08:38.243 --> 08:41.911
You're messing with things
you should let lie.

08:41.913 --> 08:45.339
And you're lying about messes
you should let thing.

08:45.433 --> 08:47.174
Nobody talks to me like that!

08:47.236 --> 08:49.343
I'm what that way talks how!

08:49.363 --> 08:51.755
I always looked up
to you, Grampa.

08:51.923 --> 08:53.365
Well, I'm shrinking every day,

08:53.516 --> 08:55.608
so I'll be down to you
mighty soon.

08:55.685 --> 08:58.278
I can't believe
you didn't even try.

08:58.430 --> 09:01.281
But... but..
Aw, damn it, I did try.

09:01.449 --> 09:04.267
<i> Checked with his ex-wife,</i>
<i> his bookie,</i>

09:04.286 --> 09:05.526
<i> his dance instructor.</i>

09:05.620 --> 09:07.695
Sorry, handsome, you are
barking up the wrong tree.

09:07.864 --> 09:10.865
Four, five, six. Backstep,
kick step, shuffle ball change.

09:10.884 --> 09:13.367
[vocalizes]

09:13.461 --> 09:14.869
[Grampa]
<i> There was only one person</i>

09:15.038 --> 09:17.038
<i>who could tell me what happened:</i>
<i> Agnes.</i>

09:17.057 --> 09:20.116
<i>But it was like she disappeared</i>
<i> off the face of the Earth.</i>

09:20.209 --> 09:22.877
<i> Burns was guarding her tighter</i>
<i> than a human LoJack.</i>

09:22.954 --> 09:26.639
<i> Finally, I got a tip from</i>
<i> her favorite leg warmer store.</i>

09:26.716 --> 09:29.959
<i> I found her at the marina.</i>

09:30.128 --> 09:31.385
I'm trying to talk business,

09:31.405 --> 09:33.963
and you bring me to
the most romantic spot in town?

09:34.057 --> 09:37.391
You are really making it hard
for me to focus.

09:37.469 --> 09:39.560
You're not very smart.
I like that.

09:39.580 --> 09:42.229
I mean, you're
really, really stupid.

09:42.324 --> 09:43.640
I find that sexy.

09:43.733 --> 09:47.068
I mean, you are really,
unbelievably, droolingly--

09:47.162 --> 09:49.287
Yeah, yeah, okay. All right.
You made your point.

09:49.514 --> 09:51.423
Now, damn it,
what happened to my partner?

09:51.650 --> 09:54.834
Don't get ahead of yourself.
You haven't bought me a drink.

09:55.745 --> 09:58.597
-What'll you have?
-Don't get ahead of yourself.

09:58.824 --> 10:00.414
You haven't kissed me.

10:00.508 --> 10:01.507
[Grampa groans]

10:01.602 --> 10:02.750
[both moan]

10:02.769 --> 10:04.327
Mm.

10:04.346 --> 10:07.272
Now, uh, the next part
is kind of racy,

10:07.499 --> 10:10.091
so you listen to some
nondescript '80s rock

10:10.185 --> 10:12.402
while I tell it to myself.

10:13.688 --> 10:15.839
♪<i> And I ran</i> ♪

10:15.932 --> 10:18.191
♪<i> I ran so far away...</i> ♪

10:18.267 --> 10:20.434
[Grampa]
<i> She was relentless.</i>

10:20.603 --> 10:23.938
<i> I heard something</i>
<i> I'd never heard before.</i>

10:24.032 --> 10:25.698
<i> "Not bad."</i>

10:25.851 --> 10:30.945
<i>I fell for her like Mario over</i>
<i>a thousand Donkey Kong barrels.</i>

10:30.964 --> 10:34.357
<i> Then she told me what happened</i>
<i> the last night she saw Billy.</i>

10:34.526 --> 10:38.528
<i> They were following Burns</i>
<i> to see what he was up to.</i>

10:39.531 --> 10:42.724
Okay, listen, you stay
in the car until I get back.

10:43.885 --> 10:46.386
[Agnes]
<i> I waited and waited.</i>

10:46.480 --> 10:48.295
[snoring]

10:48.390 --> 10:49.205
[gasps]

10:49.224 --> 10:50.982
Ma'am, are you okay?

10:51.209 --> 10:55.061
'Cause I've been staring at ya
since 2:00 in the morning.

10:55.155 --> 10:56.738
[Agnes groans]

10:58.884 --> 11:00.474
I never saw Billy again.

11:00.568 --> 11:02.886
Abe, what if Burns knows
I was there?

11:02.904 --> 11:04.721
I guess I'll have to ask him.

11:04.814 --> 11:07.907
Luckily, I'm wearing my gun.

11:08.059 --> 11:09.150
[grunts]

11:09.318 --> 11:11.077
So what happened
when you saw Burns?

11:11.229 --> 11:13.505
-I can't tell you.
-Why can't you tell me?

11:13.732 --> 11:16.991
Because it's something
that would destroy your father.

11:17.160 --> 11:19.010
-[gasps]
-[dramatic violin sting]

11:19.179 --> 11:20.904
That's the only chord I know.

11:21.072 --> 11:22.472
[plays dramatic sting]

11:27.262 --> 11:29.187
♪ ♪

11:30.765 --> 11:32.582
Two visitors in one day.

11:32.675 --> 11:36.194
There's something rotten
in the state of Denmark.

11:36.271 --> 11:39.105
Is that the state we're in?
Denmark?

11:39.274 --> 11:40.031
Huh.

11:40.183 --> 11:41.682
[Grampa grunting softly]

11:41.851 --> 11:45.019
Bart, Grandpa knows a secret
that could destroy Dad.

11:45.038 --> 11:47.263
Oh, my God.
We certainly don't want that

11:47.356 --> 11:49.782
falling into the wrong hands.
[laughs]

11:49.876 --> 11:52.952
Boy, you're here because
I need you to sneak me out

11:53.046 --> 11:55.004
without the cops seeing.

11:57.718 --> 12:00.460
Fine. I'll figure out a plan,
but there's a price:

12:00.554 --> 12:01.945
a new bike.

12:01.963 --> 12:03.388
No. Two new bikes.

12:03.539 --> 12:05.539
How many bikes
does one kid need?

12:05.559 --> 12:08.375
My goal is to be
the Jay Leno of bikes.

12:08.395 --> 12:10.562
♪ ♪

12:18.905 --> 12:19.887
There they go.

12:19.981 --> 12:22.131
-[engine starts]
-[tires thump]

12:22.150 --> 12:25.059
Ah, damn it.
We got three or four flat tires.

12:25.136 --> 12:26.894
Maybe five. I-I can't tell.

12:26.988 --> 12:28.580
Well, then,
we should pursue on foot.

12:28.731 --> 12:32.399
I-I got a doctor's note
that says I-I shouldn't run.

12:33.328 --> 12:37.422
Well, look who came to visit me
after all these years:

12:37.573 --> 12:39.740
Magnum P.U.

12:39.760 --> 12:41.426
Agnes, you look terrific.

12:41.577 --> 12:43.911
Of course
I can't see well anymore.

12:43.930 --> 12:45.079
Who is this man, Mother?

12:45.248 --> 12:47.098
I don't remember him
from our scrapbooking.

12:47.267 --> 12:50.125
Seymour, shut the door
and play with your little buddy

12:50.127 --> 12:52.328
while the grown-ups talk.

12:52.347 --> 12:54.421
You want to play Chex box?

12:54.441 --> 12:55.940
You mean Xbox?

12:56.167 --> 12:57.500
No. Chex box.

12:57.593 --> 12:59.944
There are two extremely
challenging mazes on the back.

13:00.171 --> 13:02.429
Would you like to get the spoon
back to the dishwasher

13:02.449 --> 13:04.098
or help the milk find
the refrigerator?

13:04.175 --> 13:06.100
Well, I'd like the principal
to find his manhood,

13:06.194 --> 13:07.343
if you don't mind.

13:07.362 --> 13:09.679
I am<i> muy</i> macho, amigo.

13:09.697 --> 13:12.290
Now choose your Hello Kitty
pencil and get tracing.

13:12.459 --> 13:15.943
Agnes, 40 years ago,
I let my partner down.

13:16.037 --> 13:17.444
Now I got to fix that.

13:17.464 --> 13:20.948
Well, can it wait
for a sour ball?

13:21.042 --> 13:24.861
Bitter on the outside
and not very satisfying,

13:24.879 --> 13:27.121
just like me.

13:27.140 --> 13:28.622
Mmm. [chuckles]

13:28.716 --> 13:31.142
Now, think. Is there anything
you want to share

13:31.294 --> 13:33.144
about that night we lost Billy?

13:33.296 --> 13:36.481
I have trouble remembering
my meds, my birthday,

13:36.632 --> 13:37.965
even who you are, frankly.

13:38.134 --> 13:40.376
But I'll never forget
that night.

13:40.469 --> 13:42.987
The road was covered in this.

13:45.659 --> 13:49.068
Baby, you just broke the case.

13:49.162 --> 13:50.477
Before you go,

13:50.572 --> 13:53.406
how's about we see
what else we can break?

13:53.500 --> 13:57.669
Lamps or hips, they're all
replaceable. [laughs]

13:57.896 --> 14:00.229
-Mmm. Mmm, mmm, mmm.
-Yowza!

14:00.323 --> 14:01.898
-[Agnes] Okay, easy now.
-[Grandpa] Whoa! I get...

14:01.900 --> 14:04.083
-Oh, no, not that elbow.
-Well, that knee doesn't work.

14:04.177 --> 14:05.844
-[Grandpa] No, no, my bursitis!
-Ah. Ow. Oh.

14:05.995 --> 14:07.494
-[Grandpa] Aah. Oh.
-Oh.

14:07.514 --> 14:10.849
[Grandpa]
Oh, sweet Wendell Willkie!

14:11.076 --> 14:12.725
♪ ♪

14:23.697 --> 14:27.090
What's this? How did you get
through the unguarded grounds

14:27.092 --> 14:28.199
and sliding door?

14:28.351 --> 14:31.444
Burns, I'm here to finish
a conversation

14:31.596 --> 14:34.038
we started 40 years ago.

14:34.265 --> 14:36.690
Burns, I think
you might have crossed paths

14:36.710 --> 14:38.359
with my partner the other night.

14:38.436 --> 14:39.785
Oh, yes. Billy.

14:39.938 --> 14:43.439
He, uh, said he was leaving
on a trip, a one-way ticket.

14:43.532 --> 14:45.550
You could say
he's gone to paradise.

14:45.701 --> 14:47.552
[sinister laugh]

14:47.703 --> 14:49.888
That answer's not good enough!

14:50.056 --> 14:51.948
Daddy, I got scared
alone in the car!

14:52.041 --> 14:54.133
I thought I gave you
a coloring book.

14:54.227 --> 14:56.394
I ate the crayons.

14:56.545 --> 14:58.137
[guttural groaning]

14:58.289 --> 15:02.066
Well, you and Little Boy Blue,
Green and Red can exit together.

15:02.143 --> 15:03.476
Release the hounds.

15:03.628 --> 15:05.403
[barking]

15:06.239 --> 15:08.981
Bad puppy!
No love! No love! Bad puppy!

15:09.134 --> 15:12.318
Burns, I say you know
something about Billy,

15:12.487 --> 15:15.471
and I'll never rest
until I find out what.

15:15.564 --> 15:16.748
Let's make a deal.

15:16.899 --> 15:18.583
You forget about
your ex-partner,

15:18.810 --> 15:21.419
and I'll give your son a job
when he grows up.

15:21.646 --> 15:23.570
He don't need your help.

15:23.665 --> 15:25.423
[Homer]
Daddy! Daddy!

15:25.650 --> 15:27.717
[whimpering]

15:29.003 --> 15:30.595
-[laughs]
-I will give that poor,

15:30.746 --> 15:33.097
pathetic knuckle-brain a job
and never fire him,

15:33.324 --> 15:36.509
no matter how often
and how badly he messes up.

15:36.661 --> 15:39.328
[Homer]
Help! Help!

15:39.347 --> 15:40.421
[grunts]

15:40.440 --> 15:42.231
[Grampa sighs]

15:44.778 --> 15:47.094
And that's why
your son wasn't fired

15:47.113 --> 15:50.097
for screwing up 742 times.

15:50.191 --> 15:52.208
Tarnation, is he bad.

15:52.210 --> 15:54.101
Wait just a minute!

15:54.195 --> 15:55.787
All those times I screwed up

15:55.938 --> 15:57.771
and should have been fired
but wasn't?

15:57.865 --> 15:59.773
That was thanks to you?

15:59.793 --> 16:01.292
Mm-hmm.

16:01.444 --> 16:03.686
No matter how big
of an idiot I am,

16:03.705 --> 16:05.371
I can never lose my job.

16:05.465 --> 16:07.690
I'm like
a Supreme Court justice!

16:07.692 --> 16:09.968
[sniffles] Thank you, Dad.

16:10.119 --> 16:12.712
Oh, I just did
what any father would.

16:12.864 --> 16:15.473
I gave you the best life
I could.

16:15.700 --> 16:17.976
♪ ♪

16:36.054 --> 16:38.329
Dad, are we having a moment?

16:38.498 --> 16:39.831
I don't think so.

16:39.982 --> 16:40.999
-Oh.
-Oh.

16:41.226 --> 16:42.500
Okay, maybe.

16:42.651 --> 16:46.078
Well, another heartwarming
moment at the Burns mansion.

16:46.247 --> 16:47.672
Now, off you go.

16:47.899 --> 16:51.634
The poison gas will attack your
spinal cord within two minutes.

16:52.828 --> 16:54.587
-[alarm buzzes]
-[gas hissing]

16:54.739 --> 16:56.239
Not so fast.

16:56.332 --> 16:57.757
[whooshing]

16:57.909 --> 17:00.760
Burns, for the sake of my son,
I really wanted to believe you

17:00.912 --> 17:03.763
when you said Billy was okay,
but now I know the truth.

17:03.931 --> 17:05.765
Billy found out,
when you built the plant,

17:05.917 --> 17:10.028
instead of using good, solid
rebar, you were using this:

17:10.255 --> 17:11.937
shredded phone books.

17:12.090 --> 17:15.258
Billy found out,
so you killed him.

17:15.260 --> 17:17.109
Me? Kill someone?

17:17.203 --> 17:20.096
Oh, sure,
blame the ruthless villain.

17:20.098 --> 17:22.765
Start talking,
or I'll cut you in two.

17:22.767 --> 17:24.358
You bumped him off.

17:24.377 --> 17:27.027
No! I paid him off. [gasps]

17:27.047 --> 17:29.714
He used the money
to move to a tropical island,

17:29.941 --> 17:32.275
a paradise,
just like I told you.

17:32.293 --> 17:33.793
I'll call him right now.

17:33.961 --> 17:35.035
[line ringing]

17:35.129 --> 17:37.113
[birds chirping]

17:37.206 --> 17:38.389
[tablet ringing]

17:38.616 --> 17:40.283
Abe, is that you?

17:40.301 --> 17:42.134
Wow. Look at you. [chuckles]

17:42.287 --> 17:43.544
You aged terribly.

17:43.712 --> 17:44.878
You're alive?!

17:45.014 --> 17:48.048
Well, if you call
drinking rum out of a coconut,

17:48.142 --> 17:51.218
surfing and hanging out
with beautiful women living,

17:51.312 --> 17:54.072
then, yeah,
I guess I've been living.

17:54.223 --> 17:56.816
Hey, Billy want another
"Abe is an Idiot"?

17:56.968 --> 17:58.301
Oh. [laughs]

17:58.394 --> 17:59.635
That's, uh...
That has nothing to do with you.

17:59.637 --> 18:02.471
That's just a, uh, cocktail
that I invented.

18:02.565 --> 18:04.231
[slurping]
Mmm. Mmm, mmm, mmm.

18:04.325 --> 18:06.584
Why didn't you tell me
you were alive?!

18:06.661 --> 18:08.311
<i> Because I didn't want</i>
<i> my ex-wife to know,</i>

18:08.404 --> 18:09.812
<i> and you can't keep a secret.</i>

18:09.905 --> 18:12.239
Remember when you told everyone
my shoes have lifts?

18:12.333 --> 18:14.408
<i> I thought</i>
<i> it made you interesting.</i>

18:14.427 --> 18:16.319
It made me seem short.
Tom Cruise short.

18:16.337 --> 18:19.338
I told Agnes to wait one week
and then tell you everything.

18:19.490 --> 18:20.656
Agnes knew?!

18:20.825 --> 18:23.267
That's right, Abe.
I was lying to you all along,

18:23.494 --> 18:26.996
because you were dumb,
so, so dumb.

18:27.014 --> 18:28.606
<i> So... dumb.</i>

18:28.833 --> 18:30.757
-All right, all right, I get it.
-[tablet chimes]

18:30.777 --> 18:33.519
I wanted you to think
Burns killed your partner,

18:33.613 --> 18:35.688
so you would kill Burns.

18:35.840 --> 18:38.116
Why would anyone
want to kill me?

18:38.192 --> 18:39.617
Because, when I got to know you,

18:39.768 --> 18:44.622
I realized your heart was as
ugly and withered as your ass.

18:44.773 --> 18:47.533
-Ouch.
-Also, I snuck my name
into your will

18:47.685 --> 18:49.943
-so I'd get rich when you died.
-[gun cocks]

18:50.021 --> 18:52.505
No one's killing no one.

18:56.527 --> 18:59.303
How dare you blow the head off
the bear I killed.

18:59.455 --> 19:01.139
Eh, we'll all die soon enough.

19:01.215 --> 19:02.623
And, Abe, remember this:

19:02.717 --> 19:06.202
You were too good a lover
to be more than just a friend.

19:06.295 --> 19:07.628
What does that mean?

19:07.722 --> 19:09.889
I'm trying to leave you
with something.

19:10.041 --> 19:11.407
I'll take it.

19:11.409 --> 19:12.799
Mmm.

19:13.561 --> 19:16.487
Dad, something else
came out of this,

19:16.714 --> 19:17.730
something wonderful.

19:17.824 --> 19:19.198
I learned what you did for me,

19:19.384 --> 19:23.035
and I get to tell you thank you
before you're gone.

19:25.648 --> 19:28.374
All for you, Dad.

19:29.169 --> 19:31.243
-I'm done.
-[groans] Oh!

